WEBVTT

00:00.994 --> 00:04.118
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:04.699 --> 00:18.377
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization, using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:19.118 --> 00:26.668
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:26.708 --> 00:27.890
Today,

00:27.970 --> 00:36.000
We invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:38.864 --> 00:39.524
Peace be with you.

00:40.205 --> 00:44.611
Friends, Pope Benedict memorably told us that the church does three essential things.

00:44.791 --> 00:46.473
I always found this really clarifying.

00:46.954 --> 00:54.143
The church worships God, the church evangelizes, and the church serves the poor, those three basic things.

00:54.603 --> 00:56.946
Everything we do can fit under one of those three

00:57.186 --> 00:57.566
headings.

00:57.987 --> 01:04.776
And now, if you look at the three popes prior to our present pope, you can see each one, I think, emphasizing one of those.

01:05.276 --> 01:07.559
John Paul 2, evangelization.

01:07.599 --> 01:11.985
He was the pope of the new evangelization, going around the world announcing the gospel.

01:12.566 --> 01:15.329
Pope Benedict himself, I would say, is the worship of God.

01:15.830 --> 01:19.254
That was a primary concern of his, the liturgy, the right praise of God.

01:19.915 --> 01:22.258
Pope Francis, who would doubt it, I think,

01:22.434 --> 01:25.077
care for the poor was a paramount concern of his.

01:25.577 --> 01:32.886
Now mind you, all three were interested in all three, that's true, but there was a kind of emphasis we can see in those three popes.

01:33.266 --> 01:45.600
Do you remember when Pope Francis was elected, one of his colleagues, Cardinal Hummus of Brazil, came up to him, he'd just been elected and he said, don't forget the poor.

01:46.741 --> 01:47.482
And he never did.

01:47.502 --> 01:51.506
He said at one point, remember that he wanted a poor church

01:52.194 --> 01:53.756
on behalf of the poor.

01:54.598 --> 01:58.164
And that was a light motif of a lot of his life and his teaching.

01:58.825 --> 02:05.736
You know, and in taking this on, he was standing in a very venerable tradition within Catholicism.

02:05.816 --> 02:19.858
Think of, I mean, I could name so many figures, but Mother Teresa of Calcutta, Vincent de Paul, Dorothy Day, Martin de Porres, Peter Claver, Francis of Azizi, John Chrysostom, Ambrose of Milan,

02:20.354 --> 02:23.458
The list goes on and on, up and down the centuries.

02:23.478 --> 02:31.089
Great Christian, great Catholic readers have taken the concern for the poor to be absolutely basic.

02:32.170 --> 02:37.858
Now, it stretches through the tradition, yes indeed, but all the way back to the Bible itself.

02:37.918 --> 02:43.686
I mean, Jesus, who doubts his great concern for the poor, but go back even before the Lord himself.

02:45.088 --> 02:47.491
Go back to the great Hebrew prophets.

02:48.132 --> 02:49.874
Now, I bring this up because we're reading

02:49.986 --> 02:51.648
from the prophet Amos.

02:52.989 --> 02:54.791
They all are advocates of the poor.

02:54.811 --> 02:59.697
I think of Jeremiah and Isaiah and Ezekiel and Daniel and the rest of them.

02:59.717 --> 03:07.445
But maybe Amos above all, one of the minor prophets just means he wrote a shorter book, doesn't mean he's less important than the other ones.

03:08.226 --> 03:16.636
And Amos is the great prophet, I would say, of social justice and concern for the poor.

03:17.456 --> 03:18.898
Notice, please, too, everybody,

03:19.010 --> 03:20.992
We started to take this for granted.

03:21.092 --> 03:22.774
Oh, sure, religious people are for the poor.

03:23.395 --> 03:38.292
But how revolutionary this was in the ancient world, the poor, people at the low end of the social scale that they were kind of forgotten about, marginalized figures, focuses on the rich and the powerful and the kings and generals and so on.

03:38.312 --> 03:47.442
The poor, but the great prophets of the God of Israel, their advocates of the poor, they bring the poor before

03:48.098 --> 03:49.199
the minds of the rich.

03:49.780 --> 03:51.723
Listen now to Amos.

03:51.823 --> 03:55.387
And as you do, I'm saying it to myself as I preach these words.

03:56.329 --> 03:58.451
Let these words sink in.

03:59.853 --> 04:12.569
I know people listen to me now from all over the world, but my guess is most of us listening to this sermon are, you know, fairly comfortable, fairly affluent by a worldwide standard.

04:13.451 --> 04:16.114
So listen now, all of us.

04:17.474 --> 04:33.496
whoa, to the complacent and Zion, lying on beds of ivory, stretched comfortably on their couches, improvising to the music of the harp like David, they devised their own accompaniment.

04:34.397 --> 04:35.659
Well, you can see it, can't you?

04:36.500 --> 04:37.221
Cut that image.

04:37.241 --> 04:40.085
It's very carefully painted that image.

04:41.307 --> 04:46.354
Rich, self-indulgent people lying comfortably on their couches,

04:48.450 --> 04:50.813
playing the harp to entertain themselves.

04:52.394 --> 04:54.457
It's an image of self complacency.

04:55.798 --> 05:00.324
An image, if you want, of indifference to those who don't have those same luxuries.

05:00.784 --> 05:04.148
Now Amos goes on, lest we miss the point.

05:04.208 --> 05:14.680
Listen, they drink wine from bowls and anoint themselves with the best oils, yet they're not made ill by the collapse of Joseph.

05:14.880 --> 05:16.562
Well, the first part of that,

05:17.026 --> 05:21.693
is just continuing this motif of self-indulgent, drinking wine from bowls.

05:22.494 --> 05:26.160
Something grossly indulgent is there about that image.

05:27.041 --> 05:29.085
They anoint themselves with the best oils.

05:29.966 --> 05:36.736
So, I mean, just caring for themselves preoccupied with their appearance and their well-being.

05:37.678 --> 05:40.322
And yet, they're not made ill by the collapse of Joseph.

05:40.342 --> 05:40.903
What does that mean?

05:41.424 --> 05:45.650
It means they're not bothered by the suffering of those around them.

05:46.562 --> 05:51.009
They're not bothered by those whose lives have fallen into catastrophe.

05:55.457 --> 05:55.938
Who are we?

05:56.979 --> 05:57.841
What are we like?

05:58.963 --> 06:05.273
Do we feel a little, I don't know, paying of discomfort when we hear these descriptions?

06:07.336 --> 06:08.338
How often are we

06:09.186 --> 06:12.230
preoccupied with ourselves in a self-indulgent way.

06:12.751 --> 06:16.896
How often do we sort of let the sufferings of the world just kind of roll past us?

06:19.760 --> 06:25.808
The Hebrew prophets raised their voices clearly unambiguously on behalf of the poor.

06:26.949 --> 06:32.156
Well, the first reading from Amos is just meant to set us up for the gospel.

06:32.957 --> 06:36.722
And may I say this everybody, it's the gospel of Lazarus and Diaries.

06:36.962 --> 06:38.645
The tradition calls them diavies.

06:38.725 --> 06:41.068
The gospel doesn't give them a name.

06:41.689 --> 06:44.634
Diavies just means rich man in Latin, right?

06:44.654 --> 06:46.557
So Lazarus and the rich man.

06:47.358 --> 06:50.363
I can tell you, I've been hearing this gospel all my life.

06:50.483 --> 06:56.773
I remember even as a little kid, I'd hear this terrible story and it would bother me.

06:57.714 --> 07:01.400
And I'd wonder, to what degree am I diavies?

07:01.460 --> 07:05.426
Even when I was a little guy, can I suggest

07:06.434 --> 07:09.358
That's part of the literary and spiritual power of this story.

07:09.398 --> 07:11.440
It's meant to bother us.

07:11.961 --> 07:18.188
And I don't want for a second as a preacher or interpreter to lessen that effect.

07:19.049 --> 07:20.491
You know, if anything, I want to heighten it.

07:21.833 --> 07:25.317
It seems to me that the gospel is very insistent upon this point.

07:26.078 --> 07:28.401
Well, we know the story well enough, right?

07:28.421 --> 07:30.083
Diaries, the rich man.

07:30.143 --> 07:32.165
He's dressed in purple, we hear.

07:32.225 --> 07:36.050
That's code for wealthy because only wealthy people could afford.

07:36.226 --> 07:37.989
a purple dye for their clothes.

07:40.413 --> 07:42.857
Dining sumptuously every day.

07:42.877 --> 07:46.964
And his gate is Lazarus.

07:47.044 --> 07:48.066
Now, right away, it's interesting.

07:48.647 --> 07:53.275
As I mentioned in the ancient world, especially poor people, I mean, who cares about them?

07:53.295 --> 07:54.056
They weren't mentioned.

07:54.076 --> 08:01.208
They were forgotten about the very fact that we don't know the rich man's name, but we do know Lazarus's name.

08:01.388 --> 08:02.450
That's telling.

08:03.234 --> 08:09.883
That's showing you where the priorities of the gospel writer ultimately where the priority of the God of Israel is.

08:10.724 --> 08:14.610
So Lazarus is named, but he's covered with sores.

08:15.290 --> 08:20.698
He would gladly have eaten his fill of the scraps that fell from the rich man's table.

08:23.101 --> 08:27.307
The rich man walks over Lazarus, nor is him.

08:27.948 --> 08:32.594
Lazarus would have been delighted for just a bit of the food that the rich man is eating.

08:33.154 --> 08:36.397
probably wasting and throwing away food that Lazarus would have loved.

08:38.159 --> 08:41.582
Lazarus dies, and we hear he's carried to the bosom of Abraham.

08:41.602 --> 08:44.885
It's a Jewish code for the place of paradise.

08:45.045 --> 08:45.786
He's brought to heaven.

08:46.687 --> 08:48.449
The rich man dies and is buried.

08:48.509 --> 08:54.014
So in Kenneth, this shocking sort of reversal of expectations.

08:54.034 --> 08:55.555
You'd expect, no, they're rich and powerful.

08:55.595 --> 08:56.977
They're the ones that are favored.

08:58.678 --> 08:59.339
He's buried.

08:59.399 --> 09:02.642
Lazarus is carried to the bosom of Abraham.

09:03.330 --> 09:07.254
What do we make of this, everybody?

09:09.196 --> 09:10.477
First, let it bother you.

09:12.419 --> 09:22.668
Bothers me, even as I read it again, even as I preach it for the, I don't know how many times I preach this gospel, how many times I've heard it, still bothers me.

09:24.210 --> 09:27.613
Can we hear the clear echo of Matthew 25 here?

09:28.494 --> 09:30.435
What's the difference between the saved and the damned?

09:31.136 --> 09:33.138
Well, it's not,

09:33.442 --> 09:35.864
faith or calling on the Lord's name.

09:36.485 --> 09:38.787
People that say, Lord, Lord, that doesn't matter.

09:41.310 --> 09:41.930
What matters?

09:43.452 --> 09:45.013
I was hungry and you gave me to eat.

09:45.073 --> 09:46.514
I was thirsty, you gave me to drink.

09:46.595 --> 09:49.197
I was naked and you clothed me.

09:50.899 --> 09:53.301
Lonely and you visited me in prison and you came to see me.

09:54.802 --> 09:59.407
It's these concrete acts of love on behalf of the poor.

10:00.328 --> 10:02.770
That's the difference everyone between

10:03.234 --> 10:04.756
salvation and damnation.

10:04.956 --> 10:08.160
And I don't know any softer way to put that.

10:09.402 --> 10:14.148
I don't know any other way to interpret Amos and this story.

10:16.150 --> 10:22.398
You know that a lot of sins mentioned in the Bible, to be sure, the Bible knows all about different forms of human dysfunction.

10:24.040 --> 10:31.570
But if I were to put my money on something, I'd say the one that cries out most to God is this,

10:32.386 --> 10:33.848
is indifference to the poor.

10:36.091 --> 10:41.579
What seems to make the most difference to God is how we treat those who are most in need.

10:43.301 --> 10:53.095
And how about this now from the end of the story when, when, uh, Richmond is, is in hell and there's a great chasm separating him from Lazarus and he says, let, let me, let me go back.

10:53.115 --> 10:54.497
I didn't warn my, my brothers.

10:54.537 --> 10:56.039
I had warned my family about this.

10:57.141 --> 10:58.162
And, and we get this.

10:59.810 --> 11:07.523
If they will not listen to Moses and the prophets, they will not be persuaded if someone should rise from the dead.

11:07.543 --> 11:15.797
Now, here's why I say it's a kind of damning statement because we say, well, look, Lord, just send somebody.

11:16.518 --> 11:17.980
Send someone to tell me about this.

11:19.703 --> 11:20.805
Well, whom do we have?

11:21.727 --> 11:23.269
We already have the prophets.

11:23.770 --> 11:26.194
In other words, we have Amos.

11:26.754 --> 11:27.895
We have Ezekiel.

11:27.915 --> 11:28.836
We have Isaiah.

11:28.856 --> 11:29.777
We have Jeremiah.

11:30.298 --> 11:30.958
We have them.

11:31.218 --> 11:32.820
We read from them all the time.

11:33.240 --> 11:34.742
I just read to you from Amos.

11:35.302 --> 11:36.043
We have them.

11:36.584 --> 11:41.248
If we don't listen to them, we're not even going to listen to someone who'd come back from the dead.

11:43.611 --> 11:46.874
That's a tremendous challenge, I think, to all of us.

11:48.295 --> 11:51.619
Year after year, we hear this story, don't we?

11:51.639 --> 11:54.962
Even those casual reading of the Bible would reveal this truth.

11:56.802 --> 11:59.085
That's the one that seems to matter most to God.

12:00.227 --> 12:04.554
So like in the remaining couple of minutes, can I just emphasize something I've emphasized before?

12:05.095 --> 12:07.779
You say, okay, Bishop, I get it.

12:07.799 --> 12:12.486
I hear that message, but what do you want me to do concretely?

12:13.147 --> 12:22.401
Can I suggest take open or open up your Google or something and look up the corporal works of mercy?

12:22.882 --> 12:23.583
There's seven of them.

12:24.685 --> 12:25.586
Feed the hungry.

12:26.498 --> 12:35.268
Give drink to the thirsty, shelter the homeless, visit the imprisoned, clothe the naked, bury the dead, and visit the sick.

12:36.169 --> 12:38.271
Seven, corporal works of mercy.

12:39.532 --> 12:45.459
Seven, concrete things you can do on behalf of the poor and those who suffer.

12:46.180 --> 12:49.003
It's one thing to say, oh, I'm all for social justice.

12:49.263 --> 12:49.744
Oh, so what?

12:49.804 --> 12:50.605
It's an abstraction.

12:52.066 --> 12:53.408
I'm for serving the poor.

12:53.768 --> 12:55.570
Okay, great, but what does that look like?

12:56.706 --> 13:01.290
Well, it looks like, and these are derived largely, aren't they, from Matthew 25?

13:01.350 --> 13:04.453
From the Lord's own exhortation.

13:06.135 --> 13:06.836
Feed the hungry.

13:07.136 --> 13:09.638
Are there hungry people around you?

13:10.379 --> 13:11.500
Trust me, there are.

13:11.540 --> 13:14.743
And I mean, people who are really food deprived.

13:14.903 --> 13:17.366
Wherever you're listening to me, trust me, there are.

13:17.906 --> 13:18.287
Find them.

13:18.947 --> 13:19.328
Feed them.

13:20.128 --> 13:20.709
Do something.

13:21.530 --> 13:22.391
People are thirsty.

13:22.411 --> 13:23.452
Yeah, male nourished.

13:23.592 --> 13:24.112
Absolutely.

13:24.493 --> 13:24.913
Find them.

13:25.433 --> 13:26.034
Do something.

13:26.722 --> 13:27.663
Shelter of the homeless.

13:27.943 --> 13:29.865
Homelessness is a huge problem in our country.

13:31.387 --> 13:31.847
Address it.

13:32.648 --> 13:32.949
Somehow.

13:33.389 --> 13:33.829
Find a way.

13:33.890 --> 13:34.871
Address it.

13:36.172 --> 13:36.813
Clove the naked.

13:36.833 --> 13:39.475
Are there people that they don't have enough to wear?

13:39.555 --> 13:40.416
They're that poor.

13:40.617 --> 13:41.397
Yeah, you bet.

13:41.938 --> 13:42.298
You bet.

13:42.418 --> 13:43.960
I mean, everybody lives in me right now.

13:44.441 --> 13:46.323
Even those who think, well, I'm in a very affluent area.

13:46.763 --> 13:51.668
Trust me when I tell you, not far from you, are people who are in pretty dire need.

13:52.529 --> 13:53.490
What are you doing about it?

13:53.698 --> 13:55.140
Visit the imprisoned.

13:55.520 --> 13:56.802
Is there a prison near you?

13:57.903 --> 13:58.123
Go.

13:58.684 --> 13:58.984
Visit.

13:59.765 --> 14:00.326
Do something.

14:01.127 --> 14:01.767
Minister there.

14:02.328 --> 14:03.489
Make a contribution to it.

14:05.211 --> 14:05.952
Visit the sick.

14:06.753 --> 14:09.857
We all know someone who's sick right now, don't we?

14:09.877 --> 14:11.879
We all know someone.

14:11.899 --> 14:12.520
Write them a note.

14:12.700 --> 14:13.561
Give them a phone call.

14:13.601 --> 14:14.402
Send them a text.

14:14.983 --> 14:15.663
Send them an email.

14:15.763 --> 14:16.024
Better.

14:16.705 --> 14:17.846
Go in person and visit.

14:19.388 --> 14:21.490
In other words, everybody, let this great

14:21.890 --> 14:25.897
lesson of diaries and Lazarus sink deep into your hearts.

14:26.057 --> 14:27.559
Let it bother you.

14:29.302 --> 14:31.766
And then do something about it.

14:32.988 --> 14:33.589
And God bless you.

14:37.335 --> 14:40.921
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

14:41.322 --> 14:46.450
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.

